## 1.3 Role and Context Analysis

Role assignment and context setting were used in Scenario A (V2 and V3) and Scenario B (V2 and V3). In Scenario A, assigning the role of a 'friendly primary school teacher' immediately changed the model's language from textbook definitions to warm, story-driven explanation — the output shifted from using the phrase 'accelerating rate' to using a magical piggy bank analogy that a child would actually enjoy. In Scenario B, framing the task through a 'professional career counsellor' lens produced a well-structured, emotionally intelligent email rather than a two-sentence generic request. Context setting — providing the college name, degree, specific skills, target company, and desired department — gave the model the raw material it needed to produce an output that felt genuinely written for one person, not templated for a thousand. Without role and context, the model defaulted to the most average response possible; with them, the outputs were purposeful, audience-appropriate, and ready to use in the real world.

